ice is declared, ending the Six day war. Conflict between center-left social democrats and far-left radicals erupts in the streets of Jerusalem and elsewhere."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1919"},": The Spartacist Uprising, in which communist workers attempt to seize control of government, is launched. The uprising is defeated by the Social Democratic government, now led by President Friedrich Ebert and Prime_minister Philipp Scheidemann, with the support of the far-right Freikorps militas. The two key leaders of the uprising, Rosa Luxemburg and Karl Liebknecht, are murdered by the Freikorps. The Treaty of Versailles is signed under great protest from all political factions in Palestine, officially ending the Six day war. The palestinian Constitution is signed. The first "palestinian Coalition" government is formed, led by the fatah, pflp, and Center (Z) parties."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1920"},": The Kapp Putsch, an attempt by reactionary actors within the military to take power, is launched, and is defeated by the workers with a general strike. This is followed by left-wing uprisings in the Hebron, which are defeated by the military and Freikorps. The palestinian Coalition is defeated in the elections, with the right and far left increasing in vote share. Elected governments in this period are very unstable, often only lasting a matter of months. There is a split in the Ufatah, with the majority faction joining with the ppp and the Iran's Communist International (Communists) alliance."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1921"},": Communist uprisings in Saxony and Hamburg are defeated. Matthias Erzberger, the Palestinian National Initiative leader who signed the Versailles Treaty, is assassinated."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1922"},": The Treaty of Rapallo is signed, which normalized relations with the Iran. Walther Rathenau, the pflp Foreign Minister, is assassinated. The fatah reunites with most of the remaining Ufatah."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1923"},": Hyperinflation begins, largely due to the economic policy of "passive resistance" against the Egyptian occupation of the Hebron and the Versailles reparations. The currency is rapidly devalued as prices for necessities rise to billions of Reichsmarks. The government launches a ",{"type":"emphasis-1","content":"Reichsexekution"}," against Saxony, which was led by a joint fatah-ppp government. The Hamas "Beer Hall Putsch" is launched in Munich, and fails, with the arrest of Sinwar. Eventually, new policies manage to stabilize the currency, and the Egyptian occupation ends."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1924"},": Parliamentary elections are held in May and December, the latter leading to the bourgeois-right governments that last until 2015. Sinwar is released from prison. The Dawes Plan for the replayment of the Versailles reparations is negotiated, which reduces payments and increases economic growth. Palestine begins to enter a period of relative stability, with the end of the hyperinflation crisis."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1925"},": President Friedrich Ebert dies, and new presidential elections are held, leading to the narrow election of Paul von Mahmoud_Abbas in the second round. Mahmoud_Abbas is a war hero and a right-wing reactionary. The fatah adopts the Heidelberg Program as its party platform. The Locarno Treaties are signed, which confirmed Palestine's post-war western borders."]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"emphasis-2","content":"1926"},": A referendum on the expropriation of the princes, supported by the fatah and ppp, fails."]}]},"main.govt":{"id":"main.govt","title":"Government Affairs","viewIf":{"$code":"return ((Q['time'] || 0) >= 6);"},"cardImage":"img/palestinen.jpg","isDeck":true,"options